    <item>
      <title>Re: AC Mitigation Changes – Bards and Clerics</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&amp;message.id=4617#M4617</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I think it is a good idea for the reflected mitigation of classes to follow line with the type of armor they generally wear or are restricted by and for this to be somewhat similar for all classes that wear such armor.&amp;nbsp; This follows a common sense way of thinking and most would agree that plate would provide better 'mitigation' over chain.&amp;nbsp; I allways wondered why eq used so many different variable to accomplish the same thing (I like this), yet sometimes it seems to me that the wrong variables are tweaked to affect changes instead of the more logical ones.&amp;nbsp; I wonder how you view ac soft caps and what they are supposed to reflect.&amp;nbsp; How you view over soft cap ac and what should it reflect.&amp;nbsp; When you consider over soft cap ac are you considering defense skill?&amp;nbsp; Buffs?&amp;nbsp; Total reflected ac?&amp;nbsp; Or just worn ac?&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;The reason I started questioning in this manner was because there are different soft caps, and over cap values for different classess and these don't even necessarily follow similar paths for the same armor types.&amp;nbsp; I don't feel this was necessarily an accident.&amp;nbsp; These values were deliberate and took effort to make them different.&amp;nbsp; It would have been far easier to have all such types behave the same, but they were made not to.&amp;nbsp; Why were these originally set different from eachother?&amp;nbsp; What was the thinking of the programmers/designers here?&amp;nbsp; Did they wish to reflect that there is more to fighting effectively in armor than just putting it on and getting hit?&amp;nbsp; Did they wish to reflect that certain classes tended to wear heavier armor?&amp;nbsp; Perhaps more complete armor?&amp;nbsp; Maybe they meant to show that a person that might be trying to sing while getting hit or trying to cast spells while getting swung at might not be able to properly realize the full benefits of thier armor in such a case.&amp;nbsp; Whatever the case I think they had their reasons and made them vary from eachother for a purpose that made sense to them (might be obsolete now, might not).&amp;nbsp; If you make a change in one place though, must you not also view other areas since you now have a way of thinking contrary to what was the original way?&amp;nbsp; Perhaps the returns over cap and the softcap values themselves were too good when combined with the other ac influencing skills, such as defense for instance.&amp;nbsp; Now this may not be the case, I don't know, but it would seem prudent that when altering values that others put effort into making one would be wise enough to check variables and such things that also have an affect on the overall effective results of whatever this change alters.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;To sum up, I think its good that you get an understanding of what you want things to be.&amp;nbsp; I think its good that armor types behave in a way that is logical to your understanding and the overall understanding of the community.&amp;nbsp; I think once you get your understanding you should apply that way of thinking to all similar cases and then realize the impact of what this is.&amp;nbsp; Applying to all classes and cases may reveal to you something you overlooked, or something you left out.&amp;nbsp; I think you should record your reasoning so that when someone later comes along they will understand what you were thinking before they alter to their perceptions since yours may seem completely incorrect to them.&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
