      <description>&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
toadstomp wrote:&lt;BR&gt;"After evaluating this today, we’ve decided to go ahead and increase the AC over the cap for clerics to match that of bards – so that bards and clerics will have both the same AC cap and same returns from AC over the cap, making their gains from AC be equal."&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;"As far as bards are concerned, I also looked over the AC cap values for their class. Currently, the AC value for bards is set to the same values as that of monks and rogues. This seems to also be too low and after evaluation, bards will have the same cap as clerics, which is a higher value."&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Okay... let me get this straight. First you say that the AC cap for clerics is lower than it is for bards, and you're increasing the AC cap for clerics to be the same as bards. Then you say that the AC cap for bards is lower than it is for clerics, and you're increasing the AC cap for bards to be the same as clerics.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Did I miss something?&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;It took me a moment to put it together myself 8)&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Basically he is talking about 2 different AC calculations. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The first calculation he talks about is the effective return of AC once a cleric has reached the softcap for their class (point of diminishing returns) which he is increasing.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The second calculation he talks about is the point at which Bards reach their softcap which he is raising.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;</description>
